            <div class="faq">
                <div class="faq-question" onclick="toggleAnswer(1)">
                    1. My organization is different. Can Uplifting Service still
                    work for us?
                </div>
                <div class="faq-answer" id="answer1">
                    Yes, it can! <br><br>

                    Every organization is different. But after 30+ years of
                    helping organizations around the world build distinctive
                    service cultures, I can tell you this:<br><br>

                    <strong>There is a <i>proven</i> roadmap for engineering an
                        Uplifting
                        Service culture.</strong><br><br>

                    It works in every industry and geography. It works in high
                    tech and high touch, in education, in professional services
                    and industry associations, and even in government
                    organizations.<br><br>

                    When you work with the Uplifting Service team, we will craft
                    a package of educational and support services designed to
                    help your organization travel this proven path to a culture
                    of service excellence:<br><br>

                    <p style="text-align: center;">WHY ► LEAD ► BUILD ► LEARN ►
                        DRIVE</p><br>

                    <strong> 1. Start with “Why”</strong><br>
                    Why improve your service? Why build a service culture? Why
                    build an uplifting service culture? These questions are
                    powerful tools. Your answers will lead you to clear and
                    well-defined goals – which form an essential foundation for
                    building your own uplifting service culture.<br><br>

                    <strong> 2. Take the Lead</strong><br>
                    Uplifting service cultures are not built on strict policies
                    dictated by leaders or by procedures controlled by managers.
                    Instead, these cultures grow when a shared commitment to
                    creating more value through better service permeates every
                    aspect of your business, your interactions, and your
                    transactions—from your boardroom all the way to your front
                    lines.<br><br>

                    <strong> 3. Build with the Blocks</strong><br>
                    Successful service cultures share a similar structural
                    focus. We call these “The 12 Building Blocks.” The goal, as
                    in any engineering endeavor, is to strategically organize
                    your activities and building blocks to eliminate weaknesses
                    and leverage strengths.<br><br>

                    <strong> 4. Learn to Improve</strong><br>
                    Real service education means that people learn to think and
                    act differently so that their actions always create value
                    for someone else. To achieve this throughout an organization
                    requires a common vision based on fundamental service
                    principles that apply throughout the organization.
                    Additionally, there must also be exercises customized for
                    the service situations facing each service provider, and
                    then wide-scale buy-in across the organization for the
                    attitude and practices of uplifting service.<br><br>

                    <strong> 5. Drive Forward</strong><br>
                    Building an uplifting service culture is an ongoing process
                    – and successful organizations consistently drive their
                    service forward. Leaders are skilled at sustaining focus and
                    enthusiasm for Uplifting Service. And everyone in the
                    organization is actively engaged in the process of
                    continuous service improvement.<br><br>

                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="faq">
                <div class="faq-question" onclick="toggleAnswer(2)">
                    2. What’s special about the Uplifting Service methodology?
                </div>
                <div class="faq-answer" id="answer2">
                    We believe that service excellence emerges from a strong
                    organizational culture, rather than from isolated training
                    initiatives, service scripts, and procedures.<br><br>

                    As a result, we focus on aligning leaders around a common
                    service vision, educating the team in foundational service
                    principles, and transforming the mindsets, behaviors, and
                    understanding of everyone in the organization.<br><br>

                    Over the years, we have found that some widely followed
                    practices are counterproductive. In our experience,
                    organizations can dramatically improve their odds of success
                    by following a more counterintuitive approach.<br><br>

                    So, we have developed our own rules for engineering culture
                    transformation, based on 30+ years of experience with
                    organizations in every industry and in every part of the
                    world. We call these contrarian views “The Four Rules for a
                    Service Culture Transformation.”<br><br>

                    <strong> Rule #1</strong><br>
                    Don’t start with customer-facing employees. Instead, involve
                    everyone, with a special focus on internal service
                    providers.<br><br>

                    Without a shared context and commitment to continuous
                    service improvement, employees working behind the scenes
                    often push back at those working out in the front. This
                    frustrates both parties and does little to improve service.
                    In contrast, when operational and administrative teams
                    embrace their role as service providers, front-facing teams
                    are more successful at improving the service experience for
                    clients and customers.<br><br>

                    <strong> Rule #2</strong><br>
                    Don’t start by training people in service skills, scripts,
                    and procedures. Instead, educate them first to better
                    understand what service excellence really means.<br><br>

                    Instead of focusing on tactical skills, procedural
                    compliance, and product knowledge, “transformational”
                    companies start by building a better understanding of
                    service excellence. Educating employees to act upon this
                    meaning is the spark that ignites successful
                    transformations. This approach delivers fast results as well
                    as an ongoing appetite to provide better service.<br><br>

                    <strong> Rule #3</strong><br>
                    Don’t pilot the change. Instead, go big and go fast to build
                    momentum for the new culture.<br><br>

                    Transformations succeed through dramatic change that
                    generates substantial momentum. In our experience, a gradual
                    approach to cultural change can allow outdated behaviors and
                    mindsets to endure or resurface as the campaign moves slowly
                    across the organization. A rapid and comprehensive attack
                    leaves far less room for suboptimal behaviors to hide.<br><br>

                    <strong> Rule #4</strong><br>
                    Don’t focus on traditional KPIs during the service
                    transformation. Instead, focus on leading “transformation
                    indicators.”<br><br>

                    Traditional service metrics (such as customer satisfaction
                    or Net Promoter Score) have their place. But for a service
                    transformation, these indicators come too late and do not
                    stimulate new thinking, new conversations, and new actions.
                    To get the cultural change rolling, focus on the
                    transformational indicators (such as the volume of new ideas
                    and the number of new actions taken) to build enthusiasm and
                    participation.<br><br>

                    We recommend that you review our whitepaper, <a
                        href="https://ronkaufman.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/12/UP_White-Paper_Engineering-a-Service-Culture-Transformation.pdf"
                        target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"> Engineering a
                        Service Culture Transformation</a>, to learn more about
                    how
                    organizations around the world have successfully applied
                    these four rules.<br><br>

                </div>
            </div>

